                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d537">
                <head>537. Memorandum of a Conference With the President, White House, Washington,
                    June 27, 1960, 10:22–11:14 a.m.<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d537fn1"
                        >Source: Eisenhower Library, DDE Diaries. Secret. Prepared by <persName
                            corresp="#p_GBGAJ1">Goodpaster</persName> on July 5. The time of the
                        meeting is taken from the President’s Appointment Book. (<hi rend="italic"
                            >ibid</hi>., President’s Daily Appointments)</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" from="1960-06-27T10:22:00-04:00"
                            to="1960-06-27T11:14:00-04:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">June 27, 1960</hi>, <hi rend="italic">10:22–11:14
                                a.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="participants">
                    <head>OTHERS PRESENT</head>
                    <item>Secretaries <persName corresp="#p_HCA1">Herter</persName> and <persName
                            corresp="#p_DCD1">Dillon</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>General <persName corresp="#p_GBGAJ1">Goodpaster</persName>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <p>The President said the Vice President had just suggested to him that the State
                    Department give consideration to making some kind of a general announcement
                    regarding the penetration of Communism in Latin America, bringing out
                    particularly specific actions of Moscow—for example, extension of aid and
                    particularly any shipment of arms. Mr. <persName corresp="#p_HCA1"
                        >Herter</persName> said the situation in Cuba is becoming critically bad.
                    The President commented that it would seem we should link <persName
                        corresp="#p_TMGRB1">Trujillo</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_CRF1"
                        >Castro</persName> up and direct our actions against both of them. Mr.
                        <persName corresp="#p_DCD1">Dillon</persName> said the situation regarding
                    the oil companies in Cuba is expected to come <pb facs="1001" n="969"
                        xml:id="pg_969"/> to an explosive condition this week. The refineries will
                    run out of non-Soviet crude oil, and will refuse to accept Soviet crude oil. At
                    that time they expect the Cuban government to seize the refineries.</p>
                <p>[Here followed discussion of matters unrelated to Cuba.]</p>
            </div>
